column103: For me Neural marketing is slightly off - I consider it as a tool for enhancing potential of other technologies by evaluating, which features enhance recruitment, engagement with others, data quality, etc... Thus it is a "meta technology", for experts only.

column43: New data - photos of animals that do not expect to be portraited, night photos. Feedback - just having a nice photo of wildlife that is living around you house is a great feedback. Application - although everybody can by camera trap - the usage is not without limits, e.g. not possible in cities. It cannot be carried around either.

column203: Similarly to Neural marketing, I see this partly as a meta-technology. If I understand it right, in short it means getting internet connection to places, where they were not. Then other technologies will come to play. It will not bring new data, but new in the context. I see it as extension, not novelty, then. Data quality - precise GPS coordinates.

column393: If you consider BirdNet, which is probably still not piped for distribution of alien species, or Frogs app from Australia, this the kind of feedback I have in mind - you use your recorder to understand, what is singing / calling around you, while providing important data at the same time.  It can help even experienced user with identification. Other kind of feedback might be seeing activity of bats live (https://naturesmartcities.com/). Curation - recording is still better than observation without any proof.

column243: New data - I somehow lack fantasy, but it seems obvious we can get data undreamed of. If cars, cellphones, drones communicate among each other, detectors with traps or even data loggers of birds (partly this is already happening - in case smart traps, or kakapo transmitters in New Zealand). Feedback - in fact drones could be sent automatically by a detector (to apply herbicide to a weed - this is already happening).

column343: If we could speak directly to everybody who posted a picture of potentially invasive species, we would have amazing data. But nobody has capacity for that (I mean I had, for very specific purpose). Machines could do it for us :-)

column263: Currently it is not yet for individual use, but still it could be applied on a wider scales than trained dogs (who also cannot fly). Hopefully it will become cheaper.
